[Student "S"]
{Partner's 2\H bid is a transfer; you respond 2\S. Partner now bids 3\S.   

Partner's 2\H bid is a transfer; you respond 2\S. Partner now bids 3\S.   

Partner tells you that he has only invitational strength, but has at least 6 \Ss. The \Ss are fine by you, but with only 15 HCP you decide to pass.

North plays 3\S. East leads the \DJ. UhOh. Maybe you should have bid game.

Loser List: \S = ? : \H = 1 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = ?

If the \Ss are 2-2 there will be only one loser in that suit. And maybe the \C finesse will work. 

Don't get too optimistic too early. If you play \SA and another \S you could go down. Remember that you only counted one \H loser - that means you MUST ruff a \H in your hand.  

Win the \D lead and play \HA and another \H before you touch trumps.

After this there is nothing the defense can do to stop you ruffing one \H in your hand.

Just suppose for an instant that you had played \SA and another.

East would have taken the second \S, then pulled your last \S. When the \C finesse failed you would make only 8 tricks.}
[Play "W"]DJ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AT.K743.A654.AQ5 74.AT98.QJT8.J83 KQ863.62.K73.K62 J952.QJ5.92.T974"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1NT pass 2H pass 2S pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "260fb85af449f219c2479c3db5f4a3d480e1d0dda684fcb6471f16a952d7bc9d"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{With 12 points and a 5-card Major you transfer partner to that Major. You bid 2\H. Partner bids 2\S. Now what do say next? 

With 12 points and a 5-card Major you transfer partner to that Major. You bid 2\H. Partner bids 2\S. Now what do say next?

You must insist on game, but since partner could have a doubleton \S you do so by bidding 3NT to give him the choice.

He chooses 3NT by passing.

The contract would be 3NT played by West.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \DQ. Do you win the first trick or holdup?

Winner List: \S = 3 : \H = 0 : \D = 2 : \C = 3 :: Total = 8

A holdup wouldn't hurt you since South would retain the lead. But it probably wouldn't help you much either since you do have 2 stoppers in the suit. You obviously need to establish at least one more winner in \Ss so you won't have to depend on the \HA being with North. Need it be said that \Hs is the suit you are worried about and North is the Danger hand? Let's say you win the first trick with dummy's \DK. 

Suppose you play \SA, then \S K Q. If they split 3-3 you will be soooo happy because you will make at least 10 tricks. But if North shows out on the third \S you will be pretty happy because you can give up a \S to South and still make at least 9 tricks. But if South shows out on the third \S you could be in deep trouble. You would have to give North the lead to establish an extra \S winner, and he might very well lead through your \HK. 

There is a great safety play to protect against a 4-2 \S split. Play a low \S from dummy and finesse the \ST. South may win with a doubleton \SJ but you will still make the contract. 

With this layout the safety play finesse actually works and you make an overtrick.

But visualize the \SJ and \S7 transposed. If you don't make the safety play it is true that the \SJ will fall. BUT, North will still take the fourth \S and when he gets in he will return the \HQ.}
[Play "W"]DQ

